<strong>IN&#45;TEXT CITATION</strong>
<br>
<br>
When you use another person&#8217;s ideas or words in your writing, list the authors&#8217; 
last names and any relevant page number(s), in parentheses, immediately following the cited material.
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	&hellip;was found to be the case (Smith, Spratt, and Horner 36).
</blockquote>
<br>
Or include the authors&#8217; names in your sentence, with the relevant page number(s) in parentheses.
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	Smith, Spratt, and Horner suggest that &#34;the default position is markedly affected&#34; (23).
</blockquote>
<br>
When the authors are referred to more than once in the same paragraph only the page number is needed 
for subsequent citations, as long as the work cannot be confused with others cited.
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	&hellip;was found to be the case (Smith, Spratt, and Horner 36). In addition&hellip; was a 
	common feature (28).
</blockquote>
